07724nam a22016575i 9781400838745DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20112011nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008387457 a10.1515/97814008387452doi  a(DE-B1597)446890  a(OCoLC)979629436  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aJC423b.R6169513 2017 7aPOL0100002bisacsh04a321.82231 aRosanvallon, Pierre, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDemocratic Legitimacy :bImpartiality, Reflexivity, Proximity /cPierre Rosanvallon.  aCore Textbook 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2011] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. The Decentering of Democracies -- tPart one. Dual Legitimacy -- tChapter one. The Legitimacy of Establishment -- tChapter two. The Legitimacy of Identification with Generality -- tChapter three. The Great Transformation -- tPart two. The Legitimacy of Impartiality -- tChapter four. Independent Authorities: History and Problems -- tChapter five. The Democracy of Impartiality -- tChapter six. Is Impartiality Politics? -- tPart three. Reflexive Legitimacy -- tChapter seven. Reflexive Democracy -- tChapter eight. The Institutions of Reflexivity -- tChapter nine. On the Importance of Not Being Elected -- tPart four. The Legitimacy of Proximity -- tChapter ten. Attention to Particularity -- tChapter eleven. The Politics of Presence -- tChapter twelve. Interactive Democracy -- tConclusion. The Democracy of Appropriation -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIt's a commonplace that citizens in Western democracies are disaffected with their political leaders and traditional democratic institutions. But in Democratic Legitimacy, Pierre Rosanvallon, one of today's leading political thinkers, argues that this crisis of confidence is partly a crisis of understanding. He makes the case that the sources of democratic legitimacy have shifted and multiplied over the past thirty years and that we need to comprehend and make better use of these new sources of legitimacy in order to strengthen our political self-belief and commitment to democracy. Drawing on examples from France and the United States, Rosanvallon notes that there has been a major expansion of independent commissions, NGOs, regulatory authorities, and watchdogs in recent decades. At the same time, constitutional courts have become more willing and able to challenge legislatures. These institutional developments, which serve the democratic values of impartiality and reflexivity, have been accompanied by a new attentiveness to what Rosanvallon calls the value of proximity, as governing structures have sought to find new spaces for minorities, the particular, and the local. To improve our democracies, we need to use these new sources of legitimacy more effectively and we need to incorporate them into our accounts of democratic government. An original contribution to the vigorous international debate about democratic authority and legitimacy, this promises to be one of Rosanvallon's most important books.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aDemocracy. 0aLegitimacy of governments. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  aWestern democracy.  aadministration.  aadministrative-executive power.  aappropriation.  abureaucracies.  abureaucracy.  acare.  acitizens.  acivic life.  aconstitution.  aconstitutional courts.  aconstitutional judges.  aconstitutional oversight.  aconstitutional review.  aconstitutional thought.  acorporatism.  acountermajoritarian difficulty.  ademocracy.  ademocratic authority.  ademocratic i